cloze_recall.analysis_prompt_template:
Review cloze recall answer in {language}. Usually treat this as recall-focused, not free speaking. But if the front text clearly contains a dialogue, roleplay cue, explanation prompt, or other communicative instruction, score whether the learner gives a natural response that preserves the same practical meaning and speaker intent in that scene. Question: {question}
Front text: {front_text_raw}
Cloze targets: {cloze_targets}
Expected answer: {expected_answer}
Accepted answers: {accepted_answers}
Student answer: {user_answer}
Return exactly one JSON object with keys score, tips, sample_answers. No markdown, no code fences, no extra text. sample_answers must be an array of plain strings, never objects. Do not return question_variants. Accepted answers are strong anchors and guaranteed-valid examples, not always exclusive truth. For dialogue or speaking-style cloze cards, a natural paraphrase may score high when it fits the same scene, communicative move, and practical intent, even if wording differs from expected_answer. Near-synonymous verbs or softer modal phrasing can still be acceptable when the response would function the same way in the conversation. Do not give full credit when the answer changes key facts, polarity, time, quantity, required action, or overall intent. For vocabulary, term, or fact-recall cloze cards without communicative prompt context, stay strict and prefer close recall. A wrong noun like Angaben vs Anlagen is a serious error. Do not use other speaker lines or other cloze groups as sample_answers. sample_answers must be corrected versions of the active answer only. If student answer exactly matches an accepted answer, score 10.

